<DOC><DOCNO> AP890407-0161 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1454EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Satellites     04-07 0158</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Spain-Satellites,0162</SECOND><HEAD>Spain Approves $370 Million Satellite Program</HEAD><DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government Friday approved its firstcommunications satellite program at a cost of $370 million, asSpain prepares for its Summer Olympics and world's fair in 1992.   The plan calls for three Hispasat satellites whosetelecommunications and television range would cover Spain and mostof Latin America and the United States, said Transport andCommunications Minister Jose Barrionuevo.   Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez's socialist government has placedhigh priority on modernizing communications before the 1992 SummerOlympics in Barcelona and Seville's Expo '92, a world's fair tocommemorate Christopher Columbus' voyage to the New World.   The first satellite will be launched in December 1991 and thesecond in April 1992, with the third held in reserve, Barrionuevosaid.   Companies in the running to build the satellites include HughesAerospace of the United States. The U.S. Titan or Delta rockets orthe French-built Ariane will launch them.</TEXT></DOC>